            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Tatiana Montoya-Schmidt\u2019s story is a fusion, much like the food she lovingly prepares. Born in Daly City to Filipino immigrants, her name is a tapestry of her family\u2019s history and hopes. \"Montoya\" was the Spanish surname carried from the Philippines, while \"Tatiana\" was chosen by her literature-loving mother who adored Russian novels. Growing up, her world was scented with her *lola\u2019s* (grandmother\u2019s) adobo and garlic rice, instilling in her a deep connection to food as an expression of love and identity.\n\nHer practical side led her to San Francisco State University, where she earned a Bachelor's in Hospitality Management. She honed her skills not in a classroom, but in the demanding kitchens of downtown hotels. A pivotal turning point was a six-month stage in Barcelona, where the vibrant Catalan cuisine reawakened the Spanish side of her heritage. It was there she realized her culinary voice wasn't just Filipino, but a unique blend of Pacific and Iberian flavors.\n\nBack in San Francisco, she met Karl Schmidt, a meticulous German-American business graduate with a passion for wine and service. They were a perfect pairing: her creative fire, his operational calm. After years of saving, they took a leap and opened \"Alma,\" their restaurant in the Mission District. \"Alma,\" meaning soul in Spanish, became a culinary reflection of Tatiana herself\u2014a sophisticated, soulful fusion of Filipino comfort and Spanish technique.\n\nNow at 51, Tatiana's life revolves around the restaurant she co-owns with Karl. Her 4.8-mile drive from their quiet Inner Sunset home to the vibrant chaos of the Mission is a daily ritual of transformation, shifting from wife and homeowner to Head Chef and mentor. The restaurant is successful, affording them a comfortable life but demanding nearly all their time. Tatiana dreams not of expansion or another Michelin star, but of legacy. She hopes to one day write a cookbook that tells the story of her heritage through recipes and mentor a new generation of young, female chefs of color, ensuring the flavors of her unique journey continue to be shared."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was eight, standing on a wooden stool her lolo made, the air thick with the scent of her grandmother's adobo. Her lola guided her small hand as she stirred the simmering pot, the bay leaves dancing in the dark, fragrant sauce. \"Puso, apo,\" her grandmother whispered, \"Cook with your heart.\" It wasn't a recipe; it was an inheritance. That day, Tatiana learned that love had a flavor, a scent that would anchor her entire life. It was the very beginning of her culinary soul.\n\n2.\nAt 24, she was lost and exhausted on her stage in Barcelona. Her mentor handed her a simple slice of grilled bread, rubbed with garlic and ripe tomato. The taste was an electric shock of recognition. It was the flavor of the Spanish surname her family carried from the Philippines, made real and vibrant on her tongue. In that simple bite of *pa amb tom\u00e0quet*, her culinary identity fractured and reformed. It wouldn't be just Filipino; it would be the whole story of her heritage, told on a plate.\n\n3.\nShe remembers the exact moment she knew about Karl. It was after a brutal dinner service, where she was venting over a glass of Albari\u00f1o. He didn\u2019t just sympathize; he calmly sketched a service flowchart on a cocktail napkin, his mind a quiet, orderly contrast to her creative storm. She saw it then: her passionate, fiery cooking needed his steady hand to serve it to the world. He wasn't just a man she was falling for; he was the other half of a dream she hadn't yet dared to have.\n\n4.\nIt was minutes before their first service at \"Alma.\" She and Karl stood in the silent dining room, the air humming with the ghosts of their life savings. He squeezed her hand, his own trembling slightly. In that moment, looking at the tables she\u2019d chosen and the kitchen she\u2019d designed, pure terror mixed with a profound sense of arrival. This wasn't just a restaurant; it was their shared soul, exposed and waiting for the world. It was the bravest, most vulnerable she had ever felt.\n\n5.\nJust last year, she saw her newest line cook, a young woman from Oakland, her eyes welling with frustrated tears over a broken sauce. Tatiana stopped the entire frenetic Saturday night service to gently take the whisk. \"It's okay, we can save it,\" she said softly, talking her through the fix. Seeing the wave of relief and gratitude in the young chef's eyes, Tatiana felt her ambition shift. It was no longer about the next perfect review, but about ensuring that this young woman would one day confidently lead her own kitchen."
